#3

xi<-581
xi_sq<-28507
xi_yi<-2630
yi<-53
yi_sq<-267
n<-12
SSE<-22.08
Beta_1<-(xi_yi-(xi*yi/n))/(xi_sq - ((xi^2)/n))
Beta_1
## [1] 0.1695777
SST<-(yi_sq)-((yi^2)/n)
SSR<-SST - SSE
df_error<-n-2
df_reg<-1
MSR<-SSR/df_reg
MSE<-SSE/df_error
F_obs<-MSR/MSE
p_value<-pf(4.91, 1, 10, lower.tail = F)
Y_bar<-yi/n
X_bar<-xi/n
beta_not<-Y_bar - (Beta_1*X_bar)

#complete anova table
##            df      SSE      MSE     Fobs     P-val
## Regression  1 10.83667 10.83667 4.907911 0.0510521
## Error      10 22.08000  2.20800       NA        NA
## The regression model is not statistically significant because the p-value is greater than
##     our significance level of 0.05. Hence there is no linear relationship between beta not and beta 1
#3c
R.squared<-SSR/SST
R.squared
## [1] 0.3292152
## Our R-squared value indicates that 32.92% of the data fit the regression model, which is low.
## Our residual variance is 2.208 which is also the mean squared error
## The fitted regression line is Yhat =  0.1695777 x -3.793721
#90% confidence interval
t_val<-qt(0.95, 10)
sumVal<-SSR/(Beta_1^2) #sumVal is the summation of x_i minus x_squared
SE<-sqrt(MSE/sumVal) #standard error of the slope
conF.int<-c(Beta_1 - t_val*SE, Beta_1 + t_val*SE)
conF.int
## [1] 0.03084172 0.30831371

#4e
betaNot = -8.355
beta1 = 3.243
beta2 = -1.711
varBetaNot = 292.280
varBeta1 = 0.051
varBeta2 = 0.029
tNot<-(betaNot - 0)/sqrt(varBetaNot)
t1<-(beta1 - 3)/sqrt(varBeta1)
t2<-(beta2 +1)/sqrt(varBeta2)
pt(tNot, 13)*2 #p-value for betaNot
## [1] 0.6331913
pt(t1, 13, lower.tail = F) #p-value for beta1
## [1] 0.150741
pt(t2, 13) #p-value for beta2
## [1] 0.0005444476
## Since our p-value for BetaNot is greater than alpha = 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Hence, beta_not = 0
## Since our p-value for Beta_1 is greater than alpha = 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Hence, beta_1 = 3
## Since our p-value for Beta_2 is less than alpha = 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that beta_2 = -1
